Below is an update from Western Kentucky University in Bowling Green, Kentucky.
Beginning with Spring 2021 applicants, first-time freshman
admission will be test-optional for students with an
unweighted, cumulative GPA of 2.50 or greater.
While students must have a minimum 2.0 unweighted,
cumulative GPA in order to be considered for admission, only
those with an unweighted, cumulative GPA between 2.0-2.49
will need to submit an ACT/SAT score for admission
consideration.
Select scholarships and departmental applications may still use the ACT/SAT score for admission consideration.

post_text:
SIUE's latest updates that were just announced!
1) SIUE will now not require a standardized test score for admission for spring 2021, summer 2021, or fall 2021. (www.siue.edu/undergraduate).

2) SIUE direct entry criteria has also been adjusted! This can be found here: https://www.siue.edu/undergraduate/direct-entry-meridian/index.shtml

3) SIUE is announcing the SIUE Commitment. This will be for fall 2021 IL residents. The criteria is if family income is $63,000 or less AND assets are $50,000 or less (based on FAFSA data); then SIUE will cover tuition and mandatory fees using all federal, state, and institutional aid (no loans). More details will be shared and posted on SIUE website very soon.

post_text: In order to accommodate the needs of every student and the time needed for teachers to meet those needs, plus the efforts to maintain a safe environment, Joppa/Maple Grove School District #38, will be switching to a 4-day in-person instruction starting the week of September 21, 2020. This will consist of Monday, Tuesday in-person, Wednesday Remote Learning; and then Thursday, Friday, in-person instruction. The in-person days will remain the same; 8:00 - 2:00 with Remote Learning 2:00-3:00. We will also be delivering meals on those Wednesdays. The Wednesday bus routes will run on their regular route to drop off meals beginning at 11:00, and meals will be provided at the high school for student pick-up at 11:15 to 11:45. Please reach out to your school if you desire meal delivery. Thanks so much for your understanding and flexibility.

It is time for high school seniors planning to start college in the fall of 2021 to create an FSA ID. Go to https://studentaid.gov/fsa-id/create-account/launch to create your FSA ID.

This ID will be used in October when completing the FAFSA. FAFSA results are used to determine eligibility for the MAP grant, as well as several other forms of federal, state and institutional financial assistance. The 2021-22 FAFSA, which will require 2019 income information, should be completed as soon after October 1, 2020 as possible.

post_text:
First things first: What is synchronous learning?
The first thing to know about synchronous learning is that it takes place in real-time, thus, a group of students engage in learning at the same time. At Joppa/Maple Grove USD#38, the delivery of remote learning will primarily be through synchronous learning.
Through synchronous learning, students can collaborate freely, ask questions and receive answers from the teacher in real time. The students that are in remote learning also have the opportunity to collaborate with their fellow students as if they were sitting in the classroom. We are looking forward to seeing all of you in our Google Classrooms across our district.

There will be a community and parent meeting regarding the 2020-21 school year reopening on Wednesday, July 22, at 6 pm in the Joppa Jr/Sr. High Cafeteria. Dr. Jeffrey A. Dufour

Welcome Principal, Dr. Dufour

Joppa-Maple Grove Unit School District 38 is excited to welcome Dr. Dufour as the new school principal for Joppa Jr/Sr High School and Maple Grove Elementary School. Dr. Dufour has been the Physical Education Teacher at Joppa for the last year. Prior to that, he worked in North Carolina as Assistant Principal, Athletic Director, and as a PE teacher throughout his career. His enthusiasm and love for education will enable him to foster relationships and provide the leadership to build and maintain a positive school culture.

May 7, 2020

Dear Parents,

Maple Grove Elementary will be holding its previously scheduled Pre-k registration day on Wednesday, May 13th from 8:30-2:30. It will be by appointment only. Please call the school at 543-7434 to leave a message to schedule an appointment.

To comply with social distancing guidelines, all visitors to the building must wear a mask and have their temperature taken upon entry to the building. You must wait in your car and a school staff member will let you know when we are ready.

Please have the following documents with you for registration:

Birth certificate

Social Security card

Current shots and physical

Proof of residency

Proof of income

The screening should take about 30-45 minutes.

If you have any questions, please contact aross@joppa38.com or call the school at 543-7434 and leave a message and someone will be in contact with you.

Thank you and we look forward to seeing you!

Miss Abby Ross, Pre-K Teacher

post_text:
Now more than ever is the time we are able to show the real work of all educators.
And that term "Educator" means every single person who is associated with our schools:
*The food service staff preparing meals for the community.
*The bus drivers (or other staff) who are delivering them.
*The volunteers who are supporting that work,
*The building and grounds and custodial staff who are keeping us all safe with clean buildings and offices. And will have the school spotless for when we return.
*The teachers who in a moments notice "Apollo 13'ed" this work to provide remote and continuous learning opportunities and activities.
*The staff who make sure every phone call is returned, email is responded to, etc.
*And everyone who continues to share amazing and creative ideas and stories with one another so we stay connected.

post_text:
The Joppa FFA Alumni has recently started back up! We're still in the beginning stages of getting set up, but we are making progress! The purpose of the Alumni is to promote success and growth of the students, chapter, and our community. ANYONE can join! You do not have to be a previous member to join, the only requirement is to pay your dues!

If you would like to be involved, or you have any questions, join us for the Joppa FFA Alumni Meeting on March 16th at 5:30 in the Ag room. We would love to see you there!

Our elected officers are: President - Emma Arrison, Vice President - Eliza Little, Treasurer/Secretary - Alexis Leonard

post_text: Apply for the Horatio Alger National Career & Technical Scholarship Program. Receive up to $2,500 to Pursue career and technical education. Requirements: Be enrolled in a 2 year or less career or technical degree/certificate program in Fall that will lead to employment; Attend a not-for-profit post-secondary institution; Demonstrate financial need (applicants must be Pell Grant eligible); Complete high school in the Spring; Be under the age of 30; Be a United States Citizen. Applications are due on April 15, 2020. To complete, go to application.horatioalger.org.

post_text: Last week Scholar Bowl concluded their season with back-to-back wins against Meridian. 9th-10th grade finished the season with a 10-3 record. Co-captain Hayden Forthman led the team with 610 points on the season, followed by co-captain Ava Stephens with 250 points. 11th-12th grade finished with a 4-9 record, avenging several early losses at the end of the season. Co-captain Edie Roberts led the team with 150 points followed by Matthew McHaney with 80 points. Great job to all those who competed this season!

post_text:
The Illinois Landscape Contractors Association is pleased to offer (5) $1,000 scholarships to high school seniors AND (5) scholarships to current college students interested in a horticulture related career. These scholarships are for students entering a horticultural-related degree program that includes, but is not limited to, horticulture, environmental science, landscape architecture, botany, agronomy, nursery production, ecology, agriculture, urban horticulture, floral design, and more. Each year the landscape industry hires 300,000 men and women for careers that positively impact families, their communities, and the environment. Be one of them!

All applications will be considered that are sent before March 31, 2020. The application is available online at: https://www.ilca.net/scholarship-program/

post_text: Cypress Creek National Wildlife Refuge will have summer positions for students 16 - 18 years old. These jobs are with the Youth Conservation Corps, which is a summer employment program for young men and women. Students that are selected for these positions will be involved with a variety of work projects that may include trail maintenance, mowing, boundary posting, facility maintenance and construction, and brush clearing. There will also be many opportunities to learn about the Refuge and national resource career opportunities through educational activities scheduled throughout the summer. Students who enjoy working outside and/or have an interest in a career focused on the natural resources should see Mrs. Bellamey for an application.

post_text: For the 2020-2021 academic year, one scholarship in the amount of $500 will be awarded. The scholarship is to be used for tuition, fees, books, or other related educational expenses. To be eligible, applicants must 1) be enrolled full time as a high school senior in the 2019-2020 academic year in Illinois & planning to enter college no later than the fall following graduation 2) have a strong commitment to pursue a higher education in an office professional, secretarial, or business- related field within the State of Illinois with preference given to attendance at the University of Illinois 3) involvement in co-curricular and community activities 4) demonstrate academic achievement 5) be a resident of Illinois and 6) be a citizen or permanent resident of the United States. The application is available on-line at https://publish.illinois.edu/illinois-admin-professionals/secretariat- scholarship/about-the-scholarship/

post_text:
What is the Census?
Every 10 years, the United States counts the people in this country. We call this process the Census. Everyone counts ‚Äì babies, children, teens, adults, older adults.
Why does the Census matter to me?
Illinois receives $20 billion in federal funding through U.S. Census data. This funding is important as it supports vital programs such as Medicaid, highways, and programs that help low-income households, rural communities, and communities of color. If Illinoisans are not counted during the upcoming 2020 Census, fewer resources will come to the state.
Illinois is also at risk of losing two congressional seats in the upcoming Census and will have serious political ramifications.

LEARNING IS FUN!
Maple Grove Pre-K students have been learning about different kinds of simple machines. This week they have been talking about levers and experimenting with different levers such as scissors and a balance scale and kitchen tools like tongs, a lemon juicer, and a cheese cutter! We tasted the lemons and made lemonade from the lemons we squeezed! It got a thumbs up from the students!

Before you apply, be aware that in order to qualify for or win any of the scholarships offered by Distinguished Young Women, you must participate in a program. This includes attending a rehearsal(s) and being a part of an on-stage performance. After you apply, the program you would participate in first, which is determined by where you live, will be in touch with the details of participation for their program There are no fees to enter. More information can be found at: http://distinguishedyw.org/

JHS Beta Club is requesting donations to help with our next service project. A family from Cairo, IL lost everything in a house fire. The family consists of two small boys and their mother. JHS Beta Club is requesting donations of clothing and/or monetary for food for the family. The following sizes are needed:
Ladies size 13/14 pants and XL shirts,
Childs size 4T in clothing and a size 10C in shoes,
Childs size 7 in clothing and size 1 in shoes.
The older child, age 5, had just had a birthday the day before the fire and also lost all of his gifts. Please send any donation to the school and make sure to mark it for the JHS Service Project if donating money.

post_text: The Bill of Rights Institute is asking challenging questions and rewarding students who rise to the challenge by tackling some of the most compelling questions of our time. For this year's We the Students Essay Contest, we are challenging students to tell us what civil discourse means to them. The students who provide the most thoughtful, meaningful responses to this question will receive scholarship awards of up to $7,500. A total of fourteen students will receive scholarship prizes totaling $20,000. Go to https://billofrightsinstitute.org/engage/students-programs-events/scholarship/ for more information.

post_text:
On Friday Jr High and High School, students will be finished testing at 12:19 but will be required to stay if a note is not turned in to the office.

A note is required for any student with permission to leave school after their exam period. Notes must be turned in that morning and will not be accepted as a student is checking out. The note must have students name, how they are leaving (picked up, driving, walking, leaving with....) and be signed by a parent or guardian. If students are to leave with a sibling or a friend it must be stated in the note who that person is.

Students arriving at school after the tardy bell for that exam will not be permitted in the classroom and a ZERO will be given. No early dismissals from an exam will be permitted.

Joppa's Scholar Bowl team traveled to Century to take on the Centurions. Freshmen and Sophomores won their match 220-140; with Juniors and Seniors winning their match in sudden death 60-40. Great job to all who competed!"

Overall scholar bowl report: So far the season has begun with a lot of enthusiasm by returning players and new players alike. Juniors & Seniors have a current record of 1-2, with a win over Century. A team the Seniors have never beaten in their time on Scholar Bowl. Freshmen & Sophomore team holds a record of 2-1, with wins over Century and a huge comeback victory over Dongola. All students involved have done an amazing job showing up to practices, being team leaders, and showing great attitude towards Scholar Bowl. I am very proud of all my Scholar Bowl students.

Register and complete the UW System application.
Complete all the steps through "Sign and Submit Your Application." Once you've done that, you've applied to UWM. Congratulations!
The usual next step is to "Submit Payment." You can skip this if you apply between 12:01 a.m. Dec. 14 and 11:59 p.m. Dec. 22.

post_text:
National FFA Scholarship Application is NOW LIVE!

National FFA is pleased to announce that the 2020-2021 FFA Scholarship application is now open! National FFA is once again partnering with ISTS (International Scholarship & Tuition Services) to host our scholarship application process. The scholarship platform allows students to create, edit, submit and accept their scholarship utilizing any web platform including a smart phone.

For your review, click here to view the State Staff Scholarship FAQ that outlines the improvements that were requested. Visit the FFA Scholarship website at FFA.org/Scholarships to view the new layout.

National FFA looks forward to an exciting FFA Scholarship program this year! If you have any questions, please reach out to Michelle Sullivan msullivan@FFA.org or the new Program Manager, Mark Carter, at mcarter@FFA.org

Saturday, November 23, is an Official SAT Practice Test Day SAT¬Æ. Taking a full practice test helps your students build the experience and endurance they will need to do well on the real test.
Research shows using Official SAT Practice for six to eight hours is associated with an average 90-point increase from the PSAT/NMSQT¬Æ to the SAT‚Äî30 points higher than the average for students who don‚Äôt use Official SAT Practice.

If they haven‚Äôt already, encourage your students to create their SAT practice schedules and set aside time for a practice test this Saturday. If this Saturday doesn't work for your students, they can schedule a practice test for another day.

All high school and middle school students interested in the admission process to the United States Naval Academy are encouraged to attend the informational session along with their families. To register visit: www.usna-pcni.org. If you have any questions, contact usnapcni@gmail.com.
